      </div>
    </div>

    <style>
      @media (max-width: 640px) {
        section div[style*="grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr"] {
          grid-template-columns: 1fr !important;
          gap: 32px !important;
        }
      }
    </style>
  </section>

  <!-- BOND AMOUNTS: What to Expect -->
  <section style="padding: 48px 1.5rem; background: var(--slate-50);">
    <div style="max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto;">
      <h2 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.3rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 16px;">How Much Does a Noble County Bail Bond Cost?</h2>

      <p style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 18px; padding: 16px; background: #f0f7ff; border-left: 3px solid var(--blue); border-radius: 4px;"><strong>Noble County bail bond costs are based on the charge and bail amount set by the judge. In Oklahoma, bail bond premiums are a percentage of the total bail amount. Common bail amounts in Noble County include approximately $1,000 for misdemeanor DUI, $500-$2,500 for most misdemeanors, and $5,000-$50,000+ for felony charges. Angel Bail Bonds offers competitive rates and flexible payment plans.</strong></p>

      <div style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7;">
        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">Noble County uses a bail schedule for common offenses, which allows many misdemeanor defendants to post bond immediately after booking without waiting for a judge. For felony charges, a bond hearing before a Noble County District Court judge is typically required. Bail amounts in felony cases depend on the severity of the charge, criminal history, flight risk, and community ties.</p>

        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">If the defendant does not post bail within the first 24 hours, they must appear before a judge who will formally set the bond amount. This first appearance can be conducted in person at the Noble County Courthouse or via video. Angel Bail Bonds can begin the paperwork process over the phone before even arriving at the jail, which means we can post the bond faster once we arrive in Perry.</p>

        <h3 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700; margin-top: 24px; margin-bottom: 12px;">What Payment Methods Does Angel Bail Bonds Accept for Noble County Bonds?</h3>

        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px; padding: 12px 16px; background: white; border: 1px solid var(--slate-100); border-radius: 6px;"><strong>Angel Bail Bonds accepts cash, Visa, Mastercard, Zelle, and Venmo for Noble County bail bonds. Financing is available for qualifying clients. We can process payments over the phone, making it possible to start the release process before meeting in person. There are no hidden fees.</strong></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ABOUT NOBLE COUNTY — unique local content -->
  <section style="padding: 48px 1.5rem; background: white;">
    <div style="max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto;">
      <h2 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.3rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 16px;">Where Is Noble County Jail and How Do I Get There?</h2>
      <div style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7;">
        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px; padding: 12px 16px; background: #f0f7ff; border-left: 3px solid var(--blue); border-radius: 4px;"><strong>Noble County Jail is located at 721 Cedar Street, Perry, OK 73077, near the Noble County Courthouse. Perry is 25 miles north of Stillwater via I-35 — take Exit 185 and head west into downtown Perry. The drive takes approximately 25-30 minutes. Angel Bail Bonds is one of the closest bail bond companies to Noble County Jail.</strong></p>

        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">Noble County is located in north-central Oklahoma, directly north of Payne County. The county covers approximately 740 square miles and has a population of about 11,500 residents. The county seat is Perry, a community of around 5,000 people situated along Interstate 35. Noble County was established during the Cherokee Outlet Opening of 1893 and is named after U.S. Secretary of the Interior John W. Noble.</p>

        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">The Noble County Jail is a 48-bed facility operated by the Noble County Sheriff's Office under Sheriff Charlie Hanger. The facility processes approximately 4,233 bookings per year, averaging about 8 new bookings per day. It is staffed by more than 23 officers. After booking — which includes property inventory, medical screening, and photograph — inmates are classified and assigned to housing based on their charges.</p>

        <h3 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700; margin-top: 24px; margin-bottom: 12px;">What Communities Does Angel Bail Bonds Serve in Noble County?</h3>

        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">Angel Bail Bonds serves every community in Noble County. In addition to Perry, we regularly post bonds for residents of Billings (northwest Noble County), Morrison (20 minutes west of Stillwater near the Cimarron River), Red Rock (along US-177 between Stillwater and Perry), Marland, Lucien, Ceres, and Sumner. Morrison is the closest Noble County community to our Stillwater office. No matter where in the county the arrest occurs, we respond quickly.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- COURTHOUSE + COURT INFO -->
  <section style="padding: 48px 1.5rem; background: var(--slate-50);">
    <div style="max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto;">
      <h2 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.3rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 16px;">Noble County Courthouse and Court Appearance Information</h2>

      <p style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 18px; padding: 16px; background: #f0f7ff; border-left: 3px solid var(--blue); border-radius: 4px;"><strong>The Noble County Courthouse is located at 300 Courthouse Drive, Perry, OK 73077. The Court Clerk is Hillary Vorndran, reachable at (580) 336-5187. Office hours are Monday through Friday, 8:00 AM to 4:30 PM. All Noble County criminal cases are heard in the Noble County District Court. Court dockets are available at oscn.net.</strong></p>

      <div style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7;">
        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">After posting bail and being released from Noble County Jail, the defendant must appear at all scheduled court hearings at the Noble County Courthouse. Failure to appear will result in forfeiture of the bond, a bench warrant, and additional criminal charges. Angel Bail Bonds will remind you of upcoming court dates and help ensure you understand your obligations.</p>

        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">Arraignments in Noble County typically occur within 24 hours of arrest for defendants who have not posted bail. During the arraignment, the judge informs the defendant of the charges and formally sets the bail amount. For misdemeanor cases, bail is often available through a preset bond schedule, meaning the defendant can bond out immediately after booking. Felony cases may require a separate bond hearing.</p>
      </div>

      <table style="width: 100%; font-size: 0.9rem; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 16px; background: white; border-radius: 8px; overflow: hidden; border: 1px solid var(--slate-100);">
        <tr style="background: var(--navy);">
          <td colspan="2" style="padding: 12px 16px; color: white; font-weight: 700;">Noble County Courthouse Quick Reference</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--slate-100);">
          <td style="padding: 10px 16px; color: var(--slate-400); font-weight: 600; width: 130px;">Address</td>
          <td style="padding: 10px 16px; color: var(--slate-700);">300 Courthouse Dr, Perry, OK 73077</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--slate-100);">
          <td style="padding: 10px 16px; color: var(--slate-400); font-weight: 600;">Court Clerk</td>
          <td style="padding: 10px 16px; color: var(--slate-700);">Hillary Vorndran · (580) 336-5187</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--slate-100);">
          <td style="padding: 10px 16px; color: var(--slate-400); font-weight: 600;">Office Hours</td>
          <td style="padding: 10px 16px; color: var(--slate-700);">Mon-Fri 8:00 AM - 4:30 PM</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 10px 16px; color: var(--slate-400); font-weight: 600;">Dockets</td>
          <td style="padding: 10px 16px; color: var(--slate-700);"><a href="https://www.oscn.net/dockets/" style="color: var(--blue);" target="_blank" rel="noopener">oscn.net/dockets</a></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- VISITING HOURS -->
  <section style="padding: 48px 1.5rem; background: white;">
    <div style="max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto;">
      <h2 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.3rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 16px;">What Are Noble County Jail Visiting Hours?</h2>

      <p style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 18px; padding: 16px; background: #f0f7ff; border-left: 3px solid var(--blue); border-radius: 4px;"><strong>Noble County Jail uses video visitation only — in-person visits are not currently permitted. Video visit hours are Monday through Friday 7:30 AM to 9:00 PM and Saturday through Sunday 7:30 AM to 2:30 PM. Visits are limited to 30 minutes. Call (580) 336-3517 to schedule a visit. Special visits require approval from the Sheriff, Undersheriff, or Jail Major.</strong></p>

      <div style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7;">
        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">Visitors must schedule video visits in advance by calling (580) 336-3517 or (580) 336-1001. All visitors must be at least 18 years old and have valid photo identification. The best thing you can do for your loved one while they are in Noble County Jail is to get them out. Call Angel Bail Bonds at (405) 614-3000 to start the bail process — we answer 24/7 and can often have your loved one released the same day.</p>

        <h3 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700; margin-top: 24px; margin-bottom: 12px;">How Do I Send Mail to an Inmate in Noble County Jail?</h3>

        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">Mail should be sent to the inmate's full legal name and identification number at: Noble County Jail, 721 Cedar Street, Perry, OK 73077. All incoming mail is subject to inspection. Packages and certain items may be restricted — call the jail at (580) 336-3517 for current mail policies.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHY ANGEL BAIL BONDS -->
  <section style="padding: 48px 1.5rem; background: var(--slate-50);">
    <div style="max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto;">
      <h2 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.3rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 16px;">Why Choose Angel Bail Bonds for Noble County?</h2>
      <div style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7;">
        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px; padding: 12px 16px; background: white; border: 1px solid var(--slate-100); border-radius: 6px;"><strong>Angel Bail Bonds is one of the closest bail bond companies to Noble County Jail. Located just 25 miles south in Stillwater, owner Karri McBride and her team can reach Perry in under 30 minutes. With 15+ years of experience, a 4.9-star Google rating from 127+ reviews, and 24/7 availability, Angel Bail Bonds is the trusted choice for Noble County families.</strong></p>

        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">Unlike bail bond companies based in Oklahoma City or Tulsa that may take over an hour to reach Perry, Angel Bail Bonds can often be the first bondsman on-site for Noble County arrests. Our proximity to Noble County means faster response times and faster releases. We handle the entire bail bond process with compassion and confidentiality — we understand that an arrest is one of the most stressful experiences a family can face.</p>

        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">Angel Bail Bonds is a women-owned business that has been serving Central Oklahoma for over 15 years. We offer bilingual service in English and Spanish (se habla español). Whether the arrest happens at 2 AM on a holiday weekend or during a normal business day, our team is ready to help. We also post bonds remotely by phone when possible, which can further speed up the process.</p>
      </div>
